			<ul class="comment b2" id="comment-7071668">
				
				<li class="comment-author" >
                    
                        <div class="badges">
                            
                                



                            
                        </div>
                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                

<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/discussion/avatars/2010/08/23/Runesmith/11ca14d1-c0df-4009-be32-633accbe2f22/60x60.png" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/Runesmith" title="User profile page">Runesmith</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">9 August 2010 12:17PM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>At about age 11 I had incipient flat feet and had to wear corrective shoes for a year.  Possibly as a reaction, possibly through a fascination with "wild" characters like Mowgli, I decided I didn't want to wear shoes.  My parents, gods bless them, simply made sure I had my tetanus shots, and my non-uniform school only insisted I wear sandals in the woodwork and chemistry rooms.  Apart from that and formal occasions, I didn't wear shoes for the next ten  years.  It helped that it was the hippie years, when such eccentric styles were normal.
</p><p>I noticed the difference in gym, where I could feel my balance in ways people in trainers didn't seem to.  (Being able to pick up a pencil without bending down was also useful.)  Yes, I now have wide feet which sometimes cause me problems getting fitted, in a market geared to people with shoe-shaped feet.  But when I notice the shelves of remedies for corns and bunnions, I reckon it was a gain.</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
