							<p>I hear ya, Trunkoffunk, and indeed, mindbrix.
</p><p>Sentiment sounds great -  I walk around in my socks in my office as much as I can - but as the article went on, it was clearly trying sell not just  the idea, but also the Vivo barefoot shoes. Lines like:
</p><p>"The Vivo Barefoot shoes tick all the boxes in Byrne's list of 'good shoe' requirements: a completely flexible sole, a wide and deep toebox, an anatomically correct last (the 'mould' that a shoe is built on), a closure at the back and an adjustable closure at the top, such as laces or Velcro."
</p><p>subtly suggest an answer to our childrens' shoe wearing woes....
</p><p>Good honest journalism.</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
