			<ul class="comment b2" id="comment-7078413">
				
				<li class="comment-author" >
                    
                        <div class="badges">
                            
                                



                            
                        </div>
                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                

<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/site_furniture/2010/09/01/no-user-image.gif" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/USlibrarylady" title="User profile page">USlibrarylady</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">9 August 2010 5:05PM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>Here i was, reading the article and thinking, hmm, maybe going barefoot or using very flexible shoes is a pretty good thng - and then I read how a lack of crawling may inhibit reading.
<br />     Total nonsense, and not only that, completely scientifically disproved. I was one of many children in various studies in the US alone, who were selected for study on this topic. I remember having to stay after school and being asked to crawl about the the classroom floor in kindergarten. I hated it; the floor hadn't been swept and the debris of a full day were unfortable to my chubby (and probably sticky ) palms. And since this was in the early 60's, I was required to wear a dress and didn't want my knickers to show. My mother thought the whole thing was ridiculous, since I was already reading, a skill we were only expected to learn by 1st grade. But she didn't want to stand in the way of science.
<br />    I know someone else in another state who participated in remedial crawling, as he had trouble reading. A few years later he was diagnosed with dyslexia.
<br />     I hope the podiatrist is better educated on current medical information, for her patient's sake.</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
