                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                

<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/site_furniture/2010/09/01/no-user-image.gif" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/schrodingerscat" title="User profile page">schrodingerscat</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">9 August 2010 5:45PM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p></p><blockquote><p>Crawling stimulates the brain to develop convergence of vision; people who skip this phase as babies may find it extremely difficult to learn to read and write as children</p></blockquote><p>Really?
</p><p>I thought crawling was not usually considered a developmental stage as so many babies didn't crawl, rolling, bum shuffling or just plain up and walking instead.
</p><p>Certainly of my own too it was the crawler who struggled with reading and writing. The non-crawler picked them up in about 5 minutes flat.
</p><p>I thought some of the article was interesting, some over the top, and the quote above plain nonsense. I like to go barefoot myself, as do my offspring but I don't worry overly about their shoes. After all, I used to think their father had deformed his feet with ill fitting shoes, right up until his son was born with exactly the same weird 'deformity'.</p>
						
					</div>
