							<p>Nobody really wears shoes in New Zealand, even adults in summer.  When I was a primary school some Japanese people came to visit our school and were shocked to see all the kids without shoes.  They felt sorry our parents were so poor they couldn't afford shoes so they donated each of us a pair of super-uncomfortable heavy black lace up shoes. Which we never wore, it is lucky they never came back to check!
</p><p>Kids shoes are so adorable though
</p><p>I don't know think shoes cause feet to be narrow, is that <i>scientific</i>?  I was always shoeless as a kid and my feet are too narrow for some shoes.</p><blockquote><p>My son is 16 months and has never worn a shoe, so much so that if I try to put shoes on him, he starts howling. Don't know how I am going to try and convince him for putting shoes on. Any suggestions anyone?</p></blockquote><p>mine was the same! I let him go barefoot to daycare but I put shoes in his bag, when he goes outside and his feet get cold he usually gives in. Or we give in and carry him around like a little lord, that is probably his real plan.  In summer I don't bother, if I make either of my kids wear shoes they will just take them off and lose them. I think this is completely normal, I don't worry about it. I would refuse to wear shoes too if I could.</p>
						
